<HEAD>State Department Says Elections Best Solution to Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs at end to UPDATE with Solarz calling for US military
aid to non-communist guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The best way to prevent a resurgence of power by the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is to hold free elections and let the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people reject the faction, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. But the department's statement did not rule out a role in an interim coalition government for the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, under whose former rule international human rights groups estimate one-fourth of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s 8 million people died from famine or execution. Fear of a return to power by the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the strongest of three insurgent groups in a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance coalition led by U.S.-backed Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, has been a major stumbling block to a negotiated settlement with the Vietnamese-installed government. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> is scheduled to meet with <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, the Vietnam-backed Cambodian leader, on May 2 in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> comments followed <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s announcement this week that it would pull its remaining troops out of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by the end of September, ending an 11-year occupation that ousted the communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> from power. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> totally opposes a return to dominance by the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>,'' the statement said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> envisions an arrangement in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in which an interim coalition government is headed by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, `` the logical leader of such an arrangement,'' the statement said. `` Whether the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, minus <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> and the other discredited <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> leaders who clearly must be excluded, are permitted to participate in such an interim arrangement is something the Cambodian factions themselves will have to decide,'' the department said. `` We are convinced that in free and fair elections'' for a permanent government, `` the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> people would reject the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>,'' it said. Any future arrangements for a return to democracy in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> would also have to include `` effective guarantees'' to prevent power from falling into the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the department said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say such safeguards would include an international force to monitor the Vietnamese pullout, a halt to outside supply of arms to the Cambodian factions and improved international access to the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> camps along the Thai-Cambodian border. International human rights groups and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have accused the faction of committing atrocities against prisoners taken to those camps. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> view has concerned some <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries who reject any role for the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, even an interim one, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say the group is a fact of life and has too much power in the resistance coalition to be ignored. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> announced this week that it would continue arming the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> until <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> makes good on its promise to pull out its troops, estimated to number 50,000 to 70,000. Meanwhile, Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, called Friday for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to send military aid to the forces backing <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> and one of his allies, Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should do `` everything it can'' to support the resistance against the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, who just returned from discussions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> on the situation in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He proposed that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> establish an interim government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> to set up a political settlement through elections.
