<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rights, Bjt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Activists Converge upon Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Activists were thronging to the nation's capital today for a demonstration that organizers hope will cement public opinion once and for all in favor of a woman's right to an abortion March leaders say the demonstration on Sunday will launch a campaign that includes nationwide distribution of a videotape aimed at countering the anti-abortion movement's trademark video, `` Silent Scream.'' The 20-minute videotape `` Abortion: For Survival'' includes footage of a woman undergoing an abortion to show the procedure is `` safe and simple'' and the indiscernible remains taken from the uterus in a first-trimester abortion. The videotape `` puts it where it's at,'' said <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeal </PERSON>, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority. `` It talks about abortion as a public health necessity and essential for the well-being of millions of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women. `` It features the central issue of this debate: What is abortion, why it's needed and why the public health and medical establishment of our society and worldwide is for keeping it legal.'' The tape is being distributed to government officials and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and state legislatures as well as on college campuses nationwide, she said. `` Silent Scream'' expresses the anti-abortion view by depicting a fetus being aborted. March organizers said other parts of their campaign include applying pressure on government agencies and pharmaceutical companies to improve available contraception and standing up to Operation Rescue's attempts to close down abortion clinics. The march is aimed at women's rights in general and a pending <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that could reverse its 1973 landmark ruling, <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, which legalized abortion. Oral arguments in the new case are scheduled for April 26. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told anti-abortion activists a few days after he moved into the Oval Office that he wanted the decision overturned. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> faced White House reporters on Friday but was not asked about the march or his views on abortion at a news conference that covered issues ranging from the Iran-Contra affair to the minimum wage, the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil spill to foreign policy in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. March organizers said students were coming from about 500 college campuses, many of them in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, where many college students are within easy traveling distance of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Other delegations of students as well as activists representing churches, labor unions and other groups across the country are coming. Dozens of celebrities are also scheduled to appear. <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>, said she expected the size of the demonstration will be `` easily double ... and probably -LRB- be -RRB- considerably'' larger than the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> march three years ago which drew a crowd police estimated at 90,000. A counterdemonstration by anti-abortion advocates is expected to draw about 300 people during Sunday's pro-choice march from the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument down the Mall to the Capitol.
</TEXT>
