aining wage for new hires,'' he said in a letter Friday to <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>. The latest Democratic plan was put together by <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and Sens. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. Except for minor differences on the subminimum scale, it is identical to a bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last month. In the House version, an employer could pay the lower subminimum skill only to workers in their first job. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure would require a worker to have at least 60 days' experience in one or more jobs before any employer would have to pay the higher scale. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s subminimum would allow employers to continue paying $ 3.35 to any new hires, regardless of their previous experience, for six months. That subminimum would rise to $ 3.40 an hour in 1992 under the president's proposal while the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> would do away with it entirely then.
