<HEAD>Soviet Embassy Confirms Nuclear Sub Sank Off Northern Norway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with oil slick, Russian vessels
at scene. Picks up graf 12 pvs, `It was ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Sub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet Embassy confirmed that a nuclear-powered submarine suffered an underwater accident and sank in international waters off northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, according to a radio report Saturday. Defense Minister <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said on Norwegian Radio that estimates of about 12 fatalities from the sinking Friday of the Soviet `` Mike'' class submarine appeared accurate. Some crewmen apparently were rescued, <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said but he provided no details. A Norwegian Orion reconnaissance plane saw Soviet ships and planes circling the accident site north of the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION> before nightfall Friday. A second <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> passed over the area after midnight and spotted an oil slick on the sea, <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said. He said a Soviet cruiser was en route to the scene, and that Norwegian vessels had made no attempts to approach the site, 118 miles south-southwest of <LOCATION> Bear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and 312 miles off <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Norwegian experts were meeting Saturday morning to discuss the situation and keep the government informed about the possibility of a radiation leak, the broadcast said. By Saturday, more than 12 hours after the accident, there was no word on the accident from the Soviet government or the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The sea is 6,600 feet deep at the site of the sinking, and <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said there was `` no hope'' of raising the sub from the bottom. Military officials in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said it appeared the boat caught fire underwater before breaking up and sinking. The submarine, nicknamed `` Mike'' by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, carries a crew of 95, is powered by two nuclear generators and is reportedly equipped with torpedoes and long-range ballistic missiles, Western sources say. The West German government radio also quoted <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> as saying pilots of reconnaissance planes reported seeing bodies at the site. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said there `` definitely'' were casualties aboard, but declined to estimate how many. `` The only thing we saw was an oil slick about three to four hundred meters long by 50 to 100 meters wide,'' Capt. <PERSON> Haavard </PERSON> <PERSON> Holm </PERSON>, the Orion reconnaissance pilot, said on Norwegian Radio after flying over the accident site. He said there were three Russian ships and one aircraft in the area, including a trawler, a freezer ship and what appeared to be an observation or intelligence vessel. <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said he doubted the Soviets had sent the cruiser to keep other ships away. `` They want to have as much support as possible and want to transfer the survivors and the possible dead,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said earlier that the reconnaissance plane had seen Soviet planes and boats, including rubber dinghies with people in at least one of them. It was not clear whether the people were from the submarine or the surface vessels. `` With the observations we have made with the Soviet vessels and planes in the area, it seems the Soviets can handle this case alone,'' <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> said. The area is well above the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>, but is usually ice-free because of the Gulf Stream. Temperatures in the area were near-freezing on Friday. The `` Mike'' is one of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s modern submarines, and the only one in operation, according to <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>'s Fighting Ships, the British reference book. If Western descriptions of the submarine are accurate, `` the reactors are well-protected and have less radioactive material than in older submarines.'' said <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baarli </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> He said on national radio that any radioactive material probably would remain in the sub and not escape into the sea. Norwegian and Swedish defense sources estimate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has about 110 nuclear submarines operating in northern waters from bases on the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, one of the world's heaviest concentrations of naval power. The `` Mike'' might carry 16 missiles for surface targets, although the figure is unconfirmed, said Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gur </PERSON>.
