 SULLIVAN: What was the danger in revealing the Iranian initiative in terms of the second channel and the hostages? NORTH: Well, the danger that we all saw was that you'd end up with the political fire storm we ended up with, I mean that actually happened, that you'd end up with exposure of the kind that even though officials within the Iranian government knew what was going on and officials within our government knew what was going on, that neither the Iranian public nor the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public were going to be particularly happy with this. -LRB- And -RRB- ... that the people in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> who held the hostages would be so outraged by this involvement. SULLIVAN: Was there a time when it was thought that there would be a cover story that would have to be used in order to protect the Iranian initiative? NORTH: There was a cover story. There had been a cover story _ SULLIVAN: Describe what you mean? NORTH: There had been a cover story since February of 1986 when we started to get the Hawk missiles back out of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. We told the Iranians because they were so upset with that Israeli shipment that we had nothing to do with it ... -LRB- North describes a number of `` chronologies'' that were being developed by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> in connection with the Iranian initiatives. -RRB- SULLIVAN: What was your understanding of what the president was saying publicly about these matters? NORTH: Well, the president had publicly said that they did n't happen either, which was initially part of the cover story SULLIVAN: What conclusion did you draw from that? NORTH: ... I had no idea what was in the minds of other people but it was very clear to me that the president himself out publicly on a number of occasions ... and people were digging a pretty deep hole, without me helping them, in advancing -LRB- the cover -RRB- story.
