<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Storm Calmed, Officials Now Worrying About Shifting Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crews tackling the worst oil spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history got good news from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on who's in charge of the cleanup and bad news from a weather forecast that could put untainted shoreline in jeopardy. Only 7 percent of the 10.1 million gallons of oil has been retrieved. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced Friday he was sending military troops to help clean up the oil that leaked from tanker Exxon Valdez on March 24. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was taking control of the operation, ending days of bickering and weeks of frustration over the oil company's efforts. `` I think we had a problem with organization _ that's what frustrated everybody,'' said Rear Adm. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Alaskan </LOCATION> district who now heads the cleanup operation. `` We now see a clean line of what's going to go on.'' Under the new plan, reached by compromise at the request of Alaskan officials, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> will have final responsibility for running the cleanup effort. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> will continue to provide the materials and manpower and will not be relieved of liability. `` We'll be directing the strategic application of forces. ... Exxon retains the role of support,'' said <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. The change in command came as weather forecasters warned of a change in the winds that have pushed nearly half the oil south and out of the environmentally sensitive Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> in the two weeks since the tanker ran aground on <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION>. The shift in direction threatens to push oil slicks, which have already traveled over a 3,000-square-mile area in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, toward <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the fragile bays and inlets of the <LOCATION> Kenai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. So far, only an estimated 16,000 barrels of oil have been sopped and vacuumed up from the once-clear water of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The spill has killed thousands of birds and sea otters along the central Alaskan coast, cost fishermen millions of dollars in lost catch and continues to threaten valuable salmon fisheries. A shift in the wind `` could easily double the area affected,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, coordinator of the state's cleanup effort. A large oil slick continued to threaten the edges of Kenai Fjords National Park, a remote refuge 100 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, as workers set up floating oil booms to protected against the expected onslaught. `` We're preparing for the worse case,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinley </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` Even if this does n't foul the beaches this stuff could be there for a long time. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that he was directing <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> to make military forces and equipment available. He also directed <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> to coordinate the effort. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been under pressure from members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and Alaskan officials to intervene. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> on Wednesday asked the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to take over management of the cleanup from <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>. The president insisted, however, `` We are not federalizing this operation,'' and that `` this should not relieve <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> from any of its responsibilities or liabilities.'' State officials said they were pleased with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision but worried that the use of military troops in the cleaup might disrupt the effort and deny jobs to state residents. But <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said he did n't anticipate the wholesale use of troops. `` We have a plan and we want to proceed rather cautiously,'' he said. `` What we're really going to do is have local hire.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said he was pleased with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s action, although he agrees that Alaskans should get available work before the military. `` It appears the president is meeting the objectives we had in asking the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to take over the spill cleanup in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>,'' he said.
