<HEAD>Rare Frog Found In Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Zoologists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malaya </ORGANIZATION> said today they have found a frog that grows out of an egg instead of going through the tadpole stage in water. Zoology professor <PERSON> Yong </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said he and a team of colleagues discovered a tree frog, philautus aurifasciatus, which can breed on land without water, while on a jungle expedition last February in the <LOCATION> Genting </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highlands </LOCATION> area about 20 miles east of <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>. He said the eggs were found on a pitcher plant, and were the first time such a frog had been found in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. Most frogs lay eggs in water that become tadpoles, which mature into frogs and leave the water. <PERSON> Yong </PERSON> said the tree frog the zoologists discovered lays its eggs on land and that the eggs hatch frogs. He said news of the discovery was withheld to carry out breeding and tests. The frog is one of 17 species found on Malaysian trees. There are 70 species of frogs in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. The philautus aurifasciatus also has been found in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and are known to exist in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Yong </PERSON> said.
