<HEAD>Hundreds Have Died in Accidents Aboard Nuclear Submarines Since 1954</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Sub, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet crew members have died in accidents involving nuclear-powered submarines since the first, the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nautilus </ORGANIZATION>, was launched in 1954. Here is a list of accidents which have been disclosed to the public: Oct. 3, 1986: A Soviet Yankee-class submarine, powered by two nuclear reactors and carrying up to 16 nuclear-tipped missiles, was wracked by fire and an explosion while cruising submerged about 1,000 miles off the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast. The Soviets said three sailors died in the fire and explosion, but the rest of the crew was rescued before the sub sank to the ocean floor Oct. 6. April 29, 1986: The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attack submarine <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> ran aground while passing through the Straits of <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said there were no injuries, no damage to the nuclear propulsion system and that the sub went to <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> under its own power. April 1, 1986: The USS <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, armed with nuclear-tipped Poseidon missiles, ran aground in the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Although no major injuries were reported, the damage forced the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to scrap the vessel. March 21, 1984: A Soviet submarine collided with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft carrier Kitty Hawk off <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported. Sept. 27, 1984: The USS <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON>, a Poseidon submarine, collided with barrels containing nuclear waste off the British coast, according to an anti-nuclear group. Sept. 21, 1984: The <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, an attack submarine, collided with a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> barge, causing superficial damage to the sub. Sept. 20, 1984: A Soviet Golf II class ballistic missile submarine is spotted drifting in the Sea of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with white smoke pouring from its stern. The submarine later was reported to have returned to its base in <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> under its own steam. Dec. 23, 1983: The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, a Poseidon submarine, hit a submerged object during sea trials but was not damaged. Summer 1983: A Soviet submarine sank in the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, killing 90 crew members, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence officials. Dec. 16, 1982: Two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> submarines, the <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Jolla </PERSON> and the Permit, collided during sea trials off <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> but suffered only minor damage. Nov. 30, 1982: The USS <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Edison </PERSON> collided with a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> destroyer in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported. March 24, 1982: The <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> suffered $ 2 million in damage in a collision with a Turkish freighter off the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> coast. Both were able to continue under their own power. April 9, 1981: The USS <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, a missile submarine, ran into the Japanese freighter <ORGANIZATION> Nisso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maru </ORGANIZATION>, sinking the surface vessel off the southern tip of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and killing two crewmen from the Japanese ship. Oct. 27, 1981: A Soviet Whiskey-class diesel-powered submarine ran aground in a restricted military zone in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. Aug. 23, 1980: A Soviet Echo-1-class nuclear submarine caught fire and radioed for help off <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Japanese officials later reported that nine crew men died and three were injured in what remains a mysterious accident. Feb. 5, 1977: The USS Snook collided with a sonar device being towed by a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ship, damaging the submarine's periscope and superstructure. No one was injured and there were no radiation leaks, officials said. May 21, 1968: The USS Scorpion, an attack submarine, was lost with 99 men aboard off the <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. 1968: A Soviet submarine sank off the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, according to recently declassified <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> documents. 1968: A Soviet submarine sank in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, and subsequent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attempts to recover the wreck were partially successful. April 10, 1963: The USS Thresher was lost 220 miles off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast with all 129 men aboard; an investigation found that the sub had gone into sea tests without adequate safety precautions. 1961: Members of a Soviet submarine crew died of radiation poisoning after an accident in the Baltic, according to recently declassified <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> documents.
