<FIRST>u i PM-Cholesterol-Cancer     04-08 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cholesterol-Cancer,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Links Low Cholesterol in Some Men to Greater Cancer Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new medical study says a low-fat diet may not be healthy for everyone and that a 12-year survey shows low cholesterol levels coincide with an increased risk of cancer in some men. The researchers reported in the weekly <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, published Friday, that their results also show people with high cholesterol have a greater chance of getting heart disease. That finding has been confirmed by other scientific teams and gained widespread public acceptance. However, the latest team of researchers said their results also show that low cholesterol levels sometimes coincide with a greater risk from cancer, although this link was only significant for men. They said they could not explain why these people are more at risk from cancer. They said the lower cholesterol itself could be the culprit, but that something else may be the cause instead. The study is not the first to find a link between lower cholesterol and higher cancer risk. Some researchers have suggested lower cholesterol levels are in fact the product of undiagnosed bowel cancers, because developing tumors trap cholesterol and remove it from blood. While the issue remains unsettled, many other scientists doubt high cholesterol levels help prevent cancer. The report said the survey was conducted among 15,262 people _ 7,000 men and 8,262 women aged 45 to 64 in industrial southwestern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The scientists said they found the most convincing link for lung cancer. `` The inverse association between cholesterol concentration and cancer in men was strongest for lung cancer.'' The research team was comprised <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawthorne </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>; <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Isles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lever </PERSON>, both of the blood pressure unit at the Western Infirmary at <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillis </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hole </PERSON>, both of the cancer surveillance unit at <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ruchill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. The team said more research is needed in the area. But, it added, `` We conclude that it may be a mistake to assume that dietary advice given to the general population to reduce the intake of saturated fat will necessarily reduce overall mortality.'' Low-fat diets help reduce cholesterol. The team said such diets are probably a good idea for people with high cholesterol levels. Their advice, however, was contradicted by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, director of the London-based <ORGANIZATION> Coronary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>: <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> domestic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> news </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in an interview: `` I do not believe this single research study provides a proper basis on which to change well-established medical advice to eat less saturated fat.'' He said a 1,300-page study by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, released last month, showed there is no relationship between low cholesterol and cancer. `` Our advice would be that people should eat less saturated fat if they want to live longer.'' <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> microbiologist <PERSON> Selwyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Broitman </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'s science writers' seminar in <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, on Tuesday that he has found bowel cancer can lower cholesterol in rats. A long-term study of residents of <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, revealed some people have low levels of cholesterol and an above-average risk of colon cancer, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Laszlo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'s senior vice president for research. But he said studies of entire populations in several nations show that people who eat high-fat, high-cholesterol diets tend to have a higher incidence of both heart disease and colon cancer.
</TEXT>
