<HEAD>Basques May Be Back On Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five bombs believed to have been planted by Basque separatists exploded early today at a railroad line, officials said. The attacks follow a three-month truce and could signal a new round of Basque violence. The explosives went off at two points at the railway in the northern <LOCATION> Navarre </LOCATION> region, damaging tracks and a power substation, officials said. No injuries were reported. Two hours before the predawn blasts, a man telephoned a local travelers' aid bureau and said the Basque separatist organization, known by its Basque initials <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION>, had placed several bombs on the rail line that were to explode within a few hours, the civil governor's office said. The bombings represent the first attacks linked to <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> since Jan. 8, when the group called a halt to attacks in exchange for peace talks with the government. The group wants independence for the three-province northern Basque region, but the government says it will only talk when <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> ceases fighting. <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> broke off its talks with <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, earlier this week, claiming the government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> had reneged on terms for more talks and a prolonged halt on anti-government attacks. Also today, police were investigating a mail bomb that exploded Friday in an apartment in the northern Basque town of <LOCATION> Irun </LOCATION>, seriously injuring a 27-year-old man. No group immediately claimed responsibility. Authorities said they had not ruled out the possibility that <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> was behind it. Since beginning its 21-year campaign for Basque self-determination, <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people, mainly police, military and Civil Guard officers.
