<HEAD>Museum Rejects Indian Claim on Sacred Bundle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> has refused to give a more than 150-year-old relic to a Cree Indian who ran 2,700 miles in his quest to retrieve the sacred object for his people. Museum spokesman <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurz </PERSON> said Friday that the museum sent a letter to <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thunder </PERSON>'s home in <LOCATION> Edmonton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, notifying him of the museum's decision. <PERSON> Thunder </PERSON> said he was a great-great-grandson, through adoption, of Chief Big Bear, the <LOCATION> Cree </LOCATION> leader who created the artifact _ a sacred calico-wrapped bundle holding bear claws, sweet grass and a plug of tobacco. It was meant to give his people spiritual strength and guidance. Thunder said Big Bear told him ten years ago, through dreams and visions, to retrieve the bundle and take it to his tribe in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> where it would be used in prayers and sacred Indian ceremonies. Told of the museum's refusal to give him the bundle, <PERSON> Thunder </PERSON> said: `` I had been anticipating this.'' He declined to say if he would continue efforts to retrieve the artifact. Thunder, 38, arrived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> March 21 after a run across <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, beginning in <LOCATION> Edmonton </LOCATION> Sept. 1, to draw attention to his mission. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, he met with museum officials and formally requested that the Cree artifact be returned. Big Bear made the bundle when he was about 13 years old and later wore it into battle for protection and guidance. A son of Big Bear _ <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Pimi </PERSON>, who was also known as Horse Child _ sought out a museum anthropologist who was leading an expedition into central <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and on Sept. 10, 1934, presented it to the museum for safekeeping, the museum said. Since then, it has been available only to researchers, scholars and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>. It has never been on public display. In rejecting Thunder's claim, <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION>. Freed, a museum curator who met with <PERSON> Thunder </PERSON>, wrote in his letter to Thunder `` it is our responsibility to honor -LRB- <PERSON> Pimi </PERSON>'s -RRB- wish.'' Freed also noted that other Cree Indians claim they are entitled to the bundle.
