<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The conversations begin tentatively, but the fears and frustrations of the past 11 years soon come tumbling out. It is the weariness that is most striking: weariness of war, weariness of a police state, weariness of what is perceived as the world's indifference to the superpower game being played in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` Other countries like to watch us Afghans, like we watch our dogfights, and think, ` Oh, the Afghans are killing each other again,'' said a <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> university professor who has studied in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> dogfights, which are a bit like canine wrestling matches, are seldom fatal. But the war between the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government, backed until earlier this year by Soviet troops, and Western-backed Moslem guerrillas has claimed an estimated 1 million lives since the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> took power by coup and assassination in 1978. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has estimated at least 5 million Afghans have fled the country since then, leaving a population of about 10 million. `` People are dying and suffering every day,'' the professor said, speaking on condition he not be identified further. `` It is not human to just be an observer. `` The world is silent. We are silent. We have had to learn the science of being alive. I did not join the -LRB- communist -RRB- party. The politics of silence I was following.'' The professor spoke of the frustration of not being able to find out what was happening in his own country, what <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> might be contemplating, what fighting was going on in other parts of the country. `` We used to read the <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Monde </PERSON>. They come no more,'' he said. He said he distrusted the local government-controlled news media. Across town, a silver merchant also criticized what he considered the superpowers' abandonment of responsibility. `` The Americans, the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION> think they are finished. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, they make writings on paper. They say they finish this problem,'' he said. `` But this problem is not finished. It is worse, not better.'' Under a U.N.-sponsored accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> April 14, 1988, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> withdrew the last of its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Feb. 15 of this year. But <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> continues to arm its proteges, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says it can not abandon the guerrillas, who call themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors. `` You give bombs to the mujahedeen,'' the silver merchant told an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reporter. `` The Russians give bombs to the government. You do n't die. Russians do n't die. Only Afghan people die. Maybe it is time for us to say, ` OK, finished. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> is not so bad. Let us have a quick finish.'' `` The people are weary, especially in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> when they hear of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>,'' said a 41-year-old man. His niece and her three children were killed last week while trying to leave <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, about 40 miles from the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> border, where the guerrillas have besieged government troops for the past month. He said his relatives were traveling in an army-escorted convoy that was attacked by the mujahedeen. Others, too, were killed, he said, but he did not know the numbers. `` There are problems, because the main roads are going to be closed by the mujahedeen,'' he added. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> has already felt the effects of closed roads. Food and fuel supplies have been curtailed since January, as mujahedeen forces and snowfalls blocked highways. Although the situation has eased with airlifts of flour and wheat from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and weekly food and medicine flights from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the poorest people of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> still spend hours getting bread from little bakery stalls dotted around the city. Some send their children in relays to await the crisp slabs of freshly baked nan, the bread that is the staple of the Afghan diet. Traffic on the streets of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> remains light, one-fourth or less of what it was last fall, because of gasoline rationing. `` The petrol pumps are open if you have the piece of paper from the government,'' said a shopkeeper who owns a car. `` If you want the paper, it may take three or four days. I would have to close my shop for three or four days. I have 10 children, and I must keep my shop open. I walk.''
</TEXT>
