<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia-Glance     04-08 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia-Glance,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Georgia at a Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures on the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, where ethnic disputes and nationalist demonstrations prompted authorities to send in tanks and troops:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE LAND _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> in the southern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. It is bordered by <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and at 27,000 square miles, it is smaller than <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. It includes the Abkhazian Autonomous Republic on the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> coast, the Ajar Autonomous Republic and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PEOPLE _ About 70 percent of the republic's 5.3 million people are Georgian. Among minority ethnic groups, 9 percent are Armenian, 7 percent Russian, 5 percent Azerbaijanis and 1.7 percent Abkhazian.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE ECONOMY _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is a major resort area and the fruit and vegetable basket of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. There is also mining and industry.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 POLITICAL STATUS _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is one of the 15 republics making up the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and activists are calling for secession. <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION> is an `` autonomous republic'' under the authority of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>; activists there want it to become a 16th republic of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY _ <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> is one of the oldest nations in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, with records dating back to the 3rd century B.C. It became Christian in A.D. 318. It became a part of the Russian empire in 1800 to gain protection from the Persians. It became part of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1921. In 1956, dozens of people were killed when Soviet troops fired on a memorial march for the late dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who was a Georgian. In April 1978 in <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, about 5,000 people marched in protest of plans to drop Georgian as the state language of the republic. The plans were dropped.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ABKHAZIA </LOCATION> _ The small subtropical resort area is located on the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> on the border with the Russian republic. Abkhazians number just 15 percent or 91,000 of its total population of 505,000, and they are outnumbered by both Georgians and Russians in their homeland. Abkhazians have complained for years that Georgians have interfered with their national life, but Georgians complain of discrimination in <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION>. In 1978, 12,000 people gathered in village of <LOCATION> Lichni </LOCATION> to demand that <LOCATION> Abkhazia </LOCATION> be allowed to secede from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and join the Russian republic. The demand was refused, and the local party leader was dismissed.
</TEXT>
