<HEAD>Utah Legislature Approves $5 Million Request For Fusion Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seeing a potential bonanza if two scientists' claims of a new way to create fusion prove true, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> voted to appropriate $ 5 million to accelerate the research at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>. Following assurances from Gov. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> that he was n't asking for a blank check, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> on Friday approved the funds but stressed that no money would be spent until the experiment was confirmed Neither of the two researchers who claim to have produced nuclear fusion in a test tube, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, was present. <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> and other officials say their claim, if true, could bring the state millions of dollars in patent and licensing royalties. `` I want the state to get going. We're not asking for a blank check. We just want to be able to expedite the process so that it can take us where it's going to take us,'' <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> told a joint session of the Legislature. Lawmakers also passed legislation creating a nine-member state <ORGANIZATION> Fusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to oversee the research. They approved the two bills overwhelmingly after hearing presentations from <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> and members of the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regents </ORGANIZATION>. Fusion is the energy source that powers the sun and hydrogen bombs. The energy produced by nuclear power plants comes from fission, which splits atoms. During fusion, they are joined together. Ordinarily, fusion requires extremely high heat. But <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> contend that they sustained a controlled fusion reaction at room temperature, using materials found in any college laboratory, and produced four times the amount of energy required to run the experiment. Their findings were immediately cited by some as the door to a long-range, safe, cheap energy source _ if they are confirmed by other tests and transferred to a large-scale project. However, some scientists have said they can not duplicate the experiment and doubt its validity. Legislators stressed that no money would be spent until the experiment is confirmed. `` If you're asking if there is a possibility of a runaway train, we have n't even gotten the train to move yet,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Moody </PERSON>. `` Before a single dime is spent, we have to have fusion confirmed.'' The appropriations bill allocates $ 2 million for the current fiscal budget and $ 3 million for fiscal 1990, and authorizes the new council to spend up to $ 300,000 for legal services, including patent research. Attorney General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dam </PERSON> told the body he needs at least $ 75,000 immediately to hire international patent experts to advise the state on how to protect the process.
