<HEAD>Polish Changes to Usher in New Political Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 graf to CLARIFY that communist party will compete
like any other for seats in new chamber. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``Polish lawmakers...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Laws approved by parliament this week have ushered in a new era of competitive elections in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> that will break the communist party's long monopoly on power. The laws also created a new legislative chamber that will be the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first such democratically elected body. Polish lawmakers passed their historic reforms Friday in a quick series of votes as amendments to the constitution. They created a presidency, a freely elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and new electoral laws. A Solidarity committee created by leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> plans to meet today to discuss potential opposition candidates. The constitutional amendments follow major political reforms in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which last month held its first contested elections in seven decades of communist rule. However, only candidates approved by officially sanctioned groups were allowed to run in the Soviet races. The bills stem from an agreement Wednesday in an opposition-government committee on political reform. The group formed part of two-month talks between the Solidarity-led opposition and communist authorities. The opposition agreed to participate in the Sejm, or parliament, in exchange for restoration of the legal status of the independent trade union Solidarity. The union was banned after authorities imposed martial law in December 1981. The amendments call for creating a 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to be freely elected in June. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s primary function will be to act as a control on the Sejm, especially `` in the field of human rights as well as socio-economic life,'' Wednesday's agreement said. The current 460-member <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> will remain in place as the `` supreme authority of legislative power.'' However, 35 percent of its seats will now be open to candidates independent of the Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- communist -RRB- Party. The party and its allies will occupy the other 65 percent, making the communists a minority party that must work with coalition partners to create a voting majority. Those allies, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, thus expect to gain more independence and power. The arrangement could produce some lively results in now placid chamber. Anyone who collects 3,000 signatures can run for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> or for the independent Sejm seats. Previously, only candidates approved by election commissions formed by the <ORGANIZATION> communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies could be placed on the ballot. The election law also guarantees the opposition access to state-controlled media and the chance to publish a newspaper during the campaign. The constitutiomal amendments also create a post of president, which existed in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> before World War II. While the legislative changes are meant to enhance democracy, the six-year presidency is a party-inspired brake to ensure that the party retains control for the immediate future. The president's term of office will last six years. He can refuse to sign a bill into law. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> can overrule a presidential veto with a two-thirds vote. The Sejm and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> jointly elect the president, who is expected to be Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>. He was leader when Solidarity was banned.
</TEXT>
