<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is flying the bare-bones schedule it has kept since a strike began last month while its three unions and prospective new owners meet through the weekend in hopes of making a deal to revive the carrier. The negotiations, which entered their second day today, center on concessions sought by former baseball commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> and his partners. But before agreeing to any wage and benefit cuts the unions are seeking assurances the new owners have a plan to bring bankrupt Eastern back to profitability. The two sides met most of the day Friday in sessions described by one source as `` highly preliminary'' and focused primarily on the language of the <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> group's tentative agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Talks resumed at about 10 a.m. today <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, appointed by a bankruptcy judge as examiner to oversee Eastern operations, is mediating the discussions. Union officials said it was highly unlikely a deal would be struck during the weekend. A deadline does loom, however. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>'s $ 464 million purchase agreement allows him to call off the deal if he does not reach new contract agreements with the unions by midnight Tuesday. `` This will take some time because it's not only money involved,'' said an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> official who asked not to be identified. `` How does our ownership part shape up? How do we get our passengers back? What kind of job security is involved?'' <ORGANIZATION> IAM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Conley </PERSON> said the unions would have no statement on the negotiations because both sides in the talks had agreed to a news blackout requested by the bankruptcy judge overseeing Eastern. That judge would have to approve any sale of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has been all but grounded since the Machinists struck March 4. The airline's pilots and flight attendants have honored <ORGANIZATION> IAM </ORGANIZATION> pickets. In other development, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit Friday alleging that takeover specialist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> was trying to interfere with the sale. The lawsuit in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bend </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district court near <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> charges that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has `` illegally communicated and negotiated'' with the Eastern unions. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, who made millions in the travel business before entering the sports world as head of the 1984 Olympics in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, was not on hand for the Friday talks but was expected to participate if significant progress is made. Representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants, also are involved in the talks. The <ORGANIZATION> IAM </ORGANIZATION> struck Eastern after rejecting concessions demanded by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>, according to sources, wants $ 210 million in wage and benefit concessions. <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Haber </PERSON>, general chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> 100 in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, which represents <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> mechanics and ground workers, said $ 210 million is the total amount of concessions requested earlier by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, $ 150 million of that from Machinists. He said he did not know if <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> had adopted the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> demands as his own. <PERSON> Haber </PERSON> said Machinists were willing to accept 15 percent wage and benefit concessions. Union officials have indicated a willingness to accept concessions provided Eastern was sold to a new owner. Also, <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON>'s agreements give employees a 30 percent ownership stake in return for concessions. Eastern has been flying about 110 flights a day during the strike. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said the sale agreement caused no noticeable increase in passenger loads Friday.
