<HEAD>EDS: Subs lead to CORRECT Gorbachev and 7th graf to CORRECT name
of Savannah River Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plenty of Reactors Available to Make Material for Nuclear Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even if the <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> keeps his pledge to shut down three military reactors, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will have at least 11 others able to make material for nuclear bombs, according to experts and documents available in the West. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in his latest arms control gesture, announced in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Friday that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had shut down one plutonium-enrichment reactor in 1987 and would close two more over the next two years. He said his country would stop producing weapons-grade uranium. The size and even the location of Soviet military reactors is a closely guarded secret, and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not spell out which reactors would be closed, and which or even how many would remain open. `` The difficulty we have is that he has wrapped his program in such a veil of secrecy that we can not get a reading of how much further he needs to go,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, a nuclear physicist at the Natural Resources Defense Council. `` On the uranium side, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had produced a huge surplus of weapons uranium in 1964, and shut off all production of that. What he is doing is do what we did 25 years ago,'' said <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>. The Soviets already have an estimated 115 metric tons of plutonium and 500 metric tons of enriched uranium, mostly in the 32,000 nuclear weapons thought to be in their arsenal, said <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>, co-authors of a book on the Soviet weapons complex. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has about 110 metric tons of plutonium, with further production frozen because the only three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reactors able to produce nuclear weapons materials, at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Site </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, have been shut down because they can not be operated safely. <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, who has extensive contacts with Soviet scientists and arms control officials and travels regularly to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, said he had advised the Russians to seek a freeze like the one proposed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` We pointed out to them the timeliness of this, as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> prepares to make major commitment'' to spend an estimated $ 8 billion to build a new generation of weapons reactors at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> clearly has taken a step that sends a signal that they are ready to enter negotiations on ending production of fissionable materials'' used in nuclear weapons, said <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were slow to respond to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proposal. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, at his news conference Friday, said he had not analyzed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proposal, `` so I honestly ca n't tell you that I know the full significance.'' One government expert on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear industry said it appeared that the plants mentioned in <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s announcement were being closed for safety reasons. `` My estimate is that he is making some political mileage out of steps they have taken for safety reasons,'' said the official, speaking on condition that he not be further identified. Intelligence analysts declined to divulge their data on the Soviet nuclear weapons complex, but two officials with access to the classified reports said the information provided by <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON> and <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> in telephone interviews went significantly beyond what has been disclosed in public. The Soviets maintain two major weapons complexes, one at <LOCATION> Kyshtym </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Chelyabinsk </LOCATION> and the other at <LOCATION> Tomsk </LOCATION>, deep in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>. Those two complexes apparently are the sites of 14 Soviet weapons reactors mentioned by Assistant Secretary of Energy <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> in testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. It was not clear whether that number included the one shut own in 1987. Six of the reactors, known as the <LOCATION> Troitsk </LOCATION> series, are located at <LOCATION> Kyshtym </LOCATION> and are run by the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION>, one of 12 Soviet defense industry ministries, according to government officials. The actual number of Soviet reactors able to produce weapons material may be much higher, <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> said, because they use water-cooled graphite reactors, like the RBMK reactors at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>, to make nuclear weapons materials as well as electricity for civilian use. Two of the Troistsk reactors were built in the late 1950's, a few years after the three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons production reactors at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and could be ready for retirement, according to one government analyst.
