<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sinking of a nuclear-powered submarine off the coast of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> is at least the third serious incident in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear fleet in 2 -LCB- years and comes amid growing Soviet public concern over nuclear safety. The accident came five months after a reported near-meltdown in a nuclear reactor aboard a Soviet icebreaker in the port city of <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>. That accident touched off a public outcry that prevented another nuclear-powered ship from docking in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. In October 1986, three sailors died in a fire and explosion aboard a Yankee-class nuclear-powered submarine in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> that was armed with ballistic missiles. Since the April 26, 1986, explosion and fire at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> that killed at least 31 people and sent a cloud of radiation into the atmosphere, Soviet people have become wary of nuclear power, both on land and at sea. In November, the nuclear powered icebreaker Rossiya pulled into <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>, near the border with <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, for the routine changing of a filter in one of its two pressurized reactors. A report in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Vodny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> four months after the incident said the routine job almost turned into a disastrous nuclear meltdown. According to the report, the chief physicist aboard the ship gave incorrect instructions to a reactor operator who in turn drained vital cooling water from operating reactor rather than the one shut down for the repairs. Had the water drained 30 minutes longer, a meltdown releasing radiation into the air over the city of 440,000 people would have occurred, the newspaper said. The `` situation was liquidated'' in four minutes, the newspaper's <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> correspondent said. Three days later, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said two cities and a region in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> refused entry to a nuclear-powered merchant ship, Sevmorput, which had reported fractures in its hull. `` A deficit of information, piled on top of the invisible shadow of the Chernobyl tragedy and the most complex ecological situation in the region, detonated a powerful explosion of public indignation,'' the newspaper said. Officials claimed that the hull fractures presented no danger to the nuclear plant on the ship, but the public was not assured. At last report, the ship was still anchored off <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION>, its fate undecided. Refusal of officials in the ports of <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> and Nakhodka and the region of <PERSON> Magadan </PERSON> highlighted a groundswell of public opposition to nuclear power that began with the Chernobyl disaster. The policy of glasnost, or openness, initiated by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has resulted in a growing vocal opposition to nuclear power. Officials scrapped plans to build six nuclear power stations because of safety concerns. Another plant in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> was closed after the Dec. 7 earthquake that killed 25,000 people prompted fears of a nuclear disaster. Although the sinking of a nuclear submarine off the coast of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> did not affect public safety in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, it reinforced concerns about the safety of nuclear power. With those concerns in mind, officials have apparently changed the course of the country's ambitious nuclear program. Previously, nuclear stations were concentrated in populous regions in the eastern part of the country. Hydroelectric plants now will be built to supply local power and nuclear stations will be constructed in remote regions where they will pose little danger to the public.
