<HEAD>Follow Your Nose, If You Dare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHWOOD, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you want to find <LOCATION> Richwood </LOCATION> in the next few days, just follow your nose. It's the place that smells of ramps, the wild, odoriferous leeks whose spring harvest was celebrated Saturday. `` The total thing, it stinks,'' said <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowell </PERSON>, a patrolman for the <ORGANIZATION> Richwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and a ramp eater for all of his 42 years. `` You wanted to know the truth, did n't you?'' The festival is billed as `` The Feast of The Ramson'' and pays tribute to the strongly favored leeks that grow in the nearby mountains. About 1,000 pounds of ramps were harvested this year and boiled down Saturday for the annual feed. Two days of snow did n't deter thousands of out-of-staters flocking to the little town. `` There were piles of people. There were probably more people from out of state than there are in <LOCATION> Richwood </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Cowell </PERSON> said. `` Since the coal companies shut down, there's only about 3,300 people in <LOCATION> Richwood </LOCATION>.'' The ramps, served with ham, sausage, beans, cornbread and buttermilk in a meal at <ORGANIZATION> Richwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, emit a strong odor that's been called both pleasant and malodorous. All agree the scent is long-lasting. `` The smell will last in town for four or five days, and that's no joke,'' <PERSON> Cowell </PERSON> said He advised a home remedy _ frequent gargling with vinegar _ to clear the breath in only two days or so. He said he would begin gargling Saturday night.
