<HEAD>Challenger License Plates Sales Pay For Mars Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of Challenger license plates have already paid for a memorial to the shuttle's seven astronauts and are helping to fund future trips to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, state officials say. The design on the license plate features the space shuttle rising on an orange-and-white cloud into a blue sky. It was conceived in the months following the 1986 shuttle explosion in which the seven lost their lives. The plates, costing an extra $ 15, went on sale in January 1987. More than 500,000 people have bought or renewed the plates, bringing in $ 5 million in 1987 and about $ 4.5 million last year. The state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> designated a quarter of the money for scholarships and another quarter for the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> to research manned missions to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. The rest is going to build and maintain the memorial at the Kennedy Space Center. `` To bring in $ 5 million in one year from these tags, without any advertising or promotion, boggles my mind,'' says <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Everidge </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Astronauts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Titusville </LOCATION>. `` We had no idea the tags would take off like that.'' The $ 5 million memorial, to be inaugurated in October, is 50 by 40 feet and will rotate to follow the sun. The names of the seven Challenger astronauts, along with the three killed in the Apollo fire and four who died in training accidents, were etched by laser onto its reflecting surface. The monument will stand on raised ground in front of the visitors center near the entrance to the space center.
