<HEAD>Solidarity Committee to Name Opposition Candidates for Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Solidarity trade union said Saturday it will field opposition candidates for every available seat in the two-chamber parliament in the country's first free elections since World War II. Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said the list of candidates for the June elections should be ready by late April or early May. The candidates will run under the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a group of more than 100 top union leaders and opposition intellectuals that has served as a policy council to <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> since December. They will have the full support of the independent trade union, a committee statement said. Solidarity has said it aspires to act solely as a trade union. Committee members say their group was formed as a separate political structure that shares the trade union's ideals. `` Solidarity will not organize the election campaign, it is not going to take part in elections, but is asking the Citizens' Committee to cultivate those open fields,'' <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> led the committee meeting in a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> church one day after the Sejm, or parliament, passed bills putting into law the economic and political agreements approved Wednesday by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>. The accords ended two months of talks between authorities and the opposition. The laws legalize Solidarity _ banned since martial law was declared in 1981 _ set free elections and create the post of presidency. The new parliament will consist of a newly created 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the 460-member sejm. Elections to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will be freely contested. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies will be assured 65 percent of the seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, with 35 percent reserved for independent, non-party candidates. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, with majority control of parliamnet, also would hold the presidency. The Solidarity Citizens' Committee formed subcommittees to deal with campaign organization, access to radio and television, coordination of candidates, and election newspaper and finances. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> delivered a short speech to open the meeting, which lasted more than six hours. `` Thanking you for our common great political and public victory, let me ask you to make use of this victory so we can together choose some way of putting freedom into practice,'' he said. In the past, Solidarity called for boycotts of elections to express disapproval of government policies. The boycott appeals and public dissatisfication led to low voter turnouts and finally to public rejection of a government referendum on economic reform in November 1987. The opposition agreed to participate in elections in exchange for the restoration of Solidarity's legal status. Authorities first proposed talks with the opposition on political and economic reform during the a wave of nationwide strikes in August.
