<TEXT>
 Police placed a mosque under government control Saturday, one day after Moslem extremists clashed with police after attending a prayer service at the mosque. Four people were wounded and 39 detained in the clashes Friday in <LOCATION> Fayoum </LOCATION>, about 60 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, said Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahran </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Fayoum </LOCATION>'s security chief. He said detainees included <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>, a blind preacher who was acquitted of charges connected to the 1981 assassination of President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mahran </PERSON> blamed <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> for the violence, saying that for the past eight months the sheik had `` incited his followers against the government'' in sermons he delivered at Al-Shuhada Mosque. He said <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>, spiritual leader of a fundamentalist group called Jihad that was blamed for <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s slaying, led Friday's noon prayers at the mosque and again urged worshipers to agitate against the government. After the service, <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> led a crowd of 300 to 400 worshipers from the mosque, <PERSON> Mahran </PERSON> said. Police opened fire and used batons and tear gas against more than 300 rioters after they fired pistols and hurled stones at police, <PERSON> Mahran </PERSON> said. He said a police colonel and three rioters were shot. <PERSON> Mahran </PERSON> said authorities decided Saturday to take Al-Shuhada Mosque from private ownership, put it under control of the Ministry of <LOCATION> Wakfs </LOCATION>, or Islamic charities, and appoint a new preacher as a way to keep <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> from the pulpit. <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> was charged with 23 others with the assassination of <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, who was killed at a military parade on Oc