<HEAD>Sikhs Arrested in Connection with Gandhi Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Sikhs charged with conspiracy in the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> were arrested Saturday, police said. Police Commissioner <PERSON> Arvind </PERSON> <PERSON> Inamdar </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jagmohan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tony </PERSON>, 35, and <PERSON> Dalip </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 55, both college lecturers in <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, were arrested at their homes. The men and three other Sikhs were charged Friday in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> court with waging war against the state, sedition, criminal conspiracy, murder and attempted murder. Two of the other Sikhs charged are in police custody and the third was killed in 1985 by rival Sikh militants. If convicted, the four still alive face a sentence of death by hanging. <PERSON> Inamdar </PERSON> said the five are accused of plotting Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s assassination and other `` sensational acts to create chaos, confusion and anarchy,'' as revenge for the June 1984 army raid on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, the Sikhs' holiest shrine They also are accused of organizing the July 1984 hijacking of an <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane and plotting an abortive assassination of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and her son <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> in September of that year. <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was elected prime minister after his mother's death. Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was shot and killed in the garden of her <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> residence by two Sikh bodyguards on Oct. 31, 1984. One of them was killed by other bodyguards and the second was convicted of murder and hanged. Another Sikh was convicted of conspircay in the murder and also hanged. The army raid on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> was ordered by Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to oust separatist Sikh militants entrenched in the shrine. At least 1,200 people, many of them Sikhs, died in the action. Sikh militants began fighting for a separate nation in 1982, citing discrimination by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who make up 80 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population The campaign has worsened since Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s death. In 1988, at least 2,400 people were killed in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and at least 480 have died so far this year. Sikhs form only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people but are in a majority in the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.
