<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pickup truck collided with a <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> Northern freight train Saturday afternoon, killing three people in the truck and leaving a fourth in critical condition. After the accident, authorities discovered that one of the train cars was leaking a chemical fertilizer, ammonium thiosulfate. The leak was unrelated to the accident, officials said. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, an employee of the <LOCATION> Amcare </LOCATION> ambulance service, said no one was exposed to the chemical. <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> said the fourth person in the truck was taken in critical condition to an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospital. Identities of the victims were not immediately available, but one was a child, authorities said. The collision occurred at an unguarded crossing in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> late Saturday afternoon. Other details, including the cause of the accident, were not immediately available.
