<HEAD>Foreign Policy Report to Bush Recommends No Major Initiatives Regarding
Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A major foreign policy report to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> advises no major new initiatives toward the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, an administration official said Saturday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked his advisers to `` take another look another time at the whole situation'' after receiving recommendations on relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations, said the official. The trio of reports are part of a major foreign policy review <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> initiated as he took office in January. In relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, `` I do n't see anything new,'' the official said, adding that there apparently was `` not much to change right now.'' The reports were given to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> over the past 10 days, the official said. The reports recommended some changes, including new measures involving an easing of pressure on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the official said, adding that regarding <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the most likely option was to break off diplomatic relations with the government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The official did not give further details. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in Sunday's editions that the president's advisers suggested that he maintain a middle course allowing him to view the policies of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> skeptically while responding with some bold foreign policy initiative of his own. The administration experts recommended a `` status-quo plus'' stanc