 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Payette </PERSON>, a longtime executive with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Features </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Syndicate </ORGANIZATION>, has died at the age of 75. <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> died of cancer Thursday at his <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> home. <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> joined <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, one of the forerunners of <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION>, in 1936 and established the first radio Teletype delivery of news to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the first daily overseas transmission of news pictures. He also organized Movietone News. He was former national president of <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chi </ORGANIZATION>, president of press clubs in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> was southwest division manager for <ORGANIZATION> UPI </ORGANIZATION> from 1961 to 1968, when he was named president of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Features </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In 1978, he became chairman of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION>, the parent firm of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Features </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>.