<HEAD>Democrat Readies Ethics Complaint Against Gingrich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Democrat circulated an ethics complaint among his <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> colleagues Friday charging <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Whip <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> with nine alleged violations of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules. The complaint, drawn up by Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, will be filed formally with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee early next week, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. Committee members were given advance copies of the complaint Friday, he said. Under House rules, the formal filing of such a complaint by <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> will force the ethics committee to take a vote on whether to launch an investigation of <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Republican. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s action was seen as the beginning of a Democratic counteroffensive against <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, who last year filed the ethics complaint that resulted in a lengthy investigation of Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. The ethics committee, known formally as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Official </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION>, is nearing the conclusion of its investigation of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and is expected to decide as early as next week whether to charge him with violations of House rules. The nine allegations in <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s complaint center on an unusual promotional deal for <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>'s 1984 book, `` Window of Opportunity.'' Details of the deal were disclosed last month, just before <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republicans elected <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> to their number two leadership position. On Friday, <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said the complaint was `` clearly another Democratic smear, and in this case a pathetically, poorly done one.'' He said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s complaint was poorly researched and riddled with factual errors. `` It is certainly Mr. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s right to file with the ethics committee,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said. `` In this case, it so clearly is an unresearched and unprepared document, and it so clearly demeans and distorts the ethics process that I hope that respectable and responsible Democrats will intervene.'' The deal involved 21 investors who put $ 5,000 each into a partnership formed to promote the book. In return for their investment, the partners were promised half the publisher's profits, but the publisher ended up losing money on the book and the investors got a tax writeoff <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, who co-authored the book, has said she received less than $ 10,000 of the $ 105,000 raised by the partnership for arranging the deal and coordinating the promotional effort. She also received a $ 26 tax benefit from her share of the partnership. Mrs. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said last month that the ethics committee had been consulted before the partnership contracts were signed to ensure that the arrangement did not violate any House rules. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> contends in the complaint that the promotional deal may have violated <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules limiting outside earned income and gifts that a member can receive. He said the deal also may have violated <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules governing the use of campaign funds and government resources and requiring disclosure of travel reimbursements.
