<HEAD>Former City Officials Sentenced, Fined</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former city attorney was sentenced Friday to 90 days in jail and four ex-commissioners got two years' probation on convictions for guaranteeing themselves jobs in settling a federal voting-rights lawsuit In addition to the jail sentence, attorney <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was fined $ 5,000, said <ORGANIZATION> Vermilion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s Attorney <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> DeArmond </PERSON>. `` He was the prime mover in the conspiracy,'' he said, `` the guy who orchestrated the whole thing.'' Former commissioners <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Scharlau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> each were sentenced to two years' unsupervised probation, fined $ 1,000 each and forfeited their pension rights and jobs with the city. The sentences were handed down by Circuit Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Komada </PERSON>. But the penalties were stayed and the defendants released on bond pending appeal of the case, <PERSON> DeArmond </PERSON> said. The men were convicted in February of conflict of interest, conspiracy and violation of a municipal code that bars entering into a contract for personal gain. All but <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> also were convicted of official misconduct. The case stems from a 1987 lawsuit filed under the federal Voting Rights Act. The parties reached a settlement that guaranteed the commissioners city jobs for three years after the city adopted a new form of government. The lawsuit alleged that <LOCATION> Danville </LOCATION>'s longtime mayor-commissioner form of government discriminated against blacks. The city held at-large elections of the commissioners who headed city departments and formed the City Council. Under the settlement, council members represent newly outlined city wards. Aldermanic elections were held in December 1987 and two blacks were among those elected _ the first blacks to serve on the council since the old system was adopted 60 years earlier. The settlement also specified that <PERSON> Scharlau </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> would have jobs as department heads for three years in the new system.
