<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions April 8-9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tough To Read Tea Leaves In Murky Concoction Of Economic Stats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forecasters gazing into their crystal balls say the economic picture is still fuzzy but they have started to get an image of how people are reacting to rising interest rates. A few businesses probably do n't like what they've seen so far. Car makers and big retail merchants furnished figures this past week that cast shadows of doubt about their situations. Sales of cars and trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> skidded an unexpectedly steep 18.3 percent in late March, auto manufacturers reported, and many retailers did n't ring up as much business last month as they had thought they would. The news was unsurprising given the direction interest rates have taken lately. Expensive purchases normally financed with loans _ like cars _ were predicted to shrink as consumers became obliged to spend more on things such as mortgage payments. So widely anticipated was the spending slowdown that the nation's Big Three automakers cranked up their promotional vehicles before the latest results were even in. They have been touting rebates and cut-rate financing deals, including <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s zero percent financing, to tempt customers back into the showrooms during the important spring car-buying season. Historically, March and April are the months when shoppers gear up for extra summertime driving by paying a visit to dealerships. Many may have stopped by to browse in late March but fewer than usual bought. Conventional wisdom says the incentives will breathe some oomph into auto sales, but after a short while they'll lose gusto again once bargain-hunters have had their fill. When many of nation's major retailers toted up March sales they were disappointed. Some blamed bad weather or the fact that they had one less selling day in this year's five-week period than they had last year _ which can make a big difference. Retail industry analysts agreed with those points. But in sifting through the numbers they came up with evidence that consumers are losing enthusiasm to spend money on the types of things they bought in abundance during much of the six-year economic expansion. `` I think we have a fundamental switch in consumer spending,'' says <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Consumers are spending more on services, such as travel, recreational pastimes or personal health and fitness plans `` The kind of items bought at the chain stores are less prominent in the consumer basket these days,'' according to <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>. A calculation by the securities firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> indicated sales of specialty apparel, hard goods such as home furnishings, and other general merchandise, rose just 4.6 percent in March, down from February's 7.6 percent growth. In order words, sales barely kept ahead of inflation. Retailers are justifiably reluctant to generalize based on only one month's performance. The transition from winter to summer can be an unsettled time for the weather, so shoppers frequently do n't buy clothes to freshen up their wardrobes or get new gardening gear, for instance, until they're sure warm temperatures have come to stay April could be a cruel month for car makers and general merchandisers if customers do n't act on the traditional weather cue and go out shopping. In other business and economic news this past week: _ The government reported what was desribed as an ambiguous set of statistics about the labor market The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the unemployment rate fell to 5 percent in March, a new 15-year low, from 5.1 percent the month before, even though the number of new jobs added to the economy fell to the smallest amount since August. _ <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> agreed to be acquired by an investor group led by former baseball commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> for about $ 464 million But the deal, which would give <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 30,000 employees a 30 percent stake in the airline, wo n't become final until after parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> brings Eastern out of federal bankruptcy protection, among other things. _ As junk bond enthusiasts capped an annual get-together in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and toasted <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s pioneering efforts in the high-yield, high-risk business, the former head of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION>'s junk bond operation pleaded innocent at his arraignment in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> federal court on a raft of racketeering and securities fraud
</TEXT>
