<HEAD>American Software Companies Sue Italian Firms For Copyright Infringement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> software consortium has accused three Italian firms of pirating American programs in an unprecedented copyright infringement suit, company officials said Friday. The suit, filed Thursday in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, accuses the European companies of copying without authorization software produced by <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The Elettrocarbonium SpA, <ORGANIZATION> Montedison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliate, <ORGANIZATION> Monefibre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, were named as co-defendants in <ORGANIZATION> BSA </ORGANIZATION>'s suit, but exactly what if any compensation the group was seeking was not specified. <ORGANIZATION> BSA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said the group would likely file additional lawsuits against several other companies in the months to come. `` The level of unauthorized copying of software in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> _ not only by dealers but by organizational users _ is one of the most egregious in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. The breach had cost companies trying to develop and market legitimate software hundreds of millions of dollars, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. Technical experts found evidence of widespread software duplication during inspections ordered by the Italian courts and conducted last week at two of the accused firms, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. He said more than 90 percent of the software inspected at <ORGANIZATION> Montedison </ORGANIZATION> was reproduced without authorization and 80 percent of the software inspected at <LOCATION> Elettrocarbonium </LOCATION> consisted of unauthorized copies. Officials at the Milan-based <ORGANIZATION> Montedison </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliate have denied the charges. <ORGANIZATION> BSA </ORGANIZATION> officials did not know whether <PERSON> Elettrocarbonium </PERSON> had also denied the allegations. <ORGANIZATION> BSA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pilar </PERSON> <PERSON> Cloud </PERSON> said the accused companies pirate the software by buying a single copy of a program and then duplicating it internally and reselling it. `` It's a fairly common practice internationally, but it's very illegal,'' Cloud said. `` BSA hopes to put a stop to it.'' Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> BSA </ORGANIZATION> was founded in 1988 to promote free and open trade in legitimate business software while protecting intellectual property. The consortium's membership also includes <ORGANIZATION> Aldus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Autodesk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sausalito </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> WordPerfect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Orem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
